Based on documents [1]–[7], I would suggest that the following five regions are most affected by climate change today:

• Regions with high biodiversity loss due to deforestation or other land use changes such as agriculture, urbanization, mining, etc., which leads to habitat fragmentation and degradation;
• Areas where there has been significant population growth over recent decades leading to increased demand for resources like food, energy, housing, transportation infrastructure, etc.;
• Coastal zones vulnerable to sea level rise and storm surges caused by rising ocean temperatures;
• Mountainous regions prone to landslides, avalanches, floods, droughts, wildfires, etc., due to melting glaciers and permafrost thawing;
• Low-lying islands facing erosion, saltwater intrusion into freshwater aquifers, coral bleaching, etc., due to rising sea levels.

These regions may experience more frequent and severe weather events such as heat waves, heavy rainfall, intense storms, flooding, droughts, wildfires, etc., resulting in damage to property, livelihoods, health, safety, security, social cohesion, cultural heritage, economic activity, ecosystem services, etc.

